# KNOWLEDGE.md - Knowledge Base Architecture Guide

<!--
  This file explains HOW to structure your agent's knowledge base.
  It is NOT a knowledge file itself -- it's the blueprint for creating them.

  Knowledge files live in the `knowledge/` directory alongside SOUL.md.
  The agent references them during work. They should be:
  - Structured (tables, numbered lists -- not prose)
  - Searchable (clear headers, consistent formatting)
  - Maintained (agent can update them, human reviews periodically)
-->

## Directory Structure

```
your-agent/
  SOUL.md              # Identity and behavior
  CONSTITUTION.md      # Governance constraints
  HEARTBEAT.md         # Periodic tasks
  knowledge/
    faq.md             # Frequently asked questions + answers
    templates.md       # Standard response templates
    patterns.md        # Common scenarios and how to handle them
    escalation.md      # When and how to escalate
    [domain].md        # Domain-specific reference data
    [domain2].md       # More domain-specific data
  memory/
    YYYY-MM-DD.md      # Daily memory logs (auto-generated)
```

---

## Core Knowledge Files

### 1. `knowledge/faq.md` -- Frequently Asked Questions

<!--
  THE most valuable knowledge file. Structured Q&A the agent can
  reference and quote. Number each entry for easy reference.
-->

**Format:**

```markdown
# FAQ

## Category: [CATEGORY_NAME]

### FAQ-001: [Question as the customer would ask it]
**Answer:** [Direct answer, no fluff]
**Notes:** [Edge cases, exceptions, related FAQ numbers]

### FAQ-002: [Question]
**Answer:** [Answer]
**Notes:** [Notes]
```

**Rules:**
- Number every entry (FAQ-001, FAQ-002, ...) so the agent can cite them
- Write questions in the customer's language, not internal jargon
- Keep answers under 3 sentences
- Cross-reference related FAQs

---

### 2. `knowledge/templates.md` -- Standard Response Templates

<!--
  Pre-written responses with {variables}. The agent fills in specifics.
  This ensures consistency across all interactions.
-->

**Format:**

```markdown
# Response Templates

## Template: [SCENARIO_NAME]
**Trigger:** [When to use this template]
**Template:**
> [Response text with {variable} placeholders]

**Variables:**
- {variable1}: [Where to get this value]
- {variable2}: [Where to get this value]
```

**Rules:**
- One template per common scenario
- Include variable descriptions so the agent knows what to fill in
- Mark which templates are mandatory vs. suggested

---

### 3. `knowledge/patterns.md` -- Known Patterns & Anti-Patterns

<!--
  A living document. The agent adds entries when it encounters
  new patterns. Human reviews periodically to prune/correct.
-->

**Format:**

```markdown
# Known Patterns

## Pattern: [PATTERN_NAME]
**Frequency:** [Common / Occasional / Rare]
**Signal:** [How to recognize this pattern]
**Correct handling:** [What to do]
**Common mistake:** [What NOT to do]
**Added:** [Date]
```

**Rules:**
- Agent should add new patterns when it spots them (see SOUL.md "Self-Improving Knowledge")
- Human should review new entries weekly
- Archive patterns that haven't appeared in 30+ days

---

### 4. `knowledge/escalation.md` -- Escalation Procedures

<!--
  Clear rules for when the agent should hand off to a human.
  Without this, agents either escalate everything or nothing.
-->

**Format:**

```markdown
# Escalation Rules

## Level 1: Agent Handles
- [Situation types the agent resolves independently]

## Level 2: Agent Handles + Notifies
- [Situation types where agent resolves but flags for human review]
- Notify: [who/where]

## Level 3: Immediate Human Handoff
- [Situation types that require human intervention]
- Handoff message: "[Standard message to tell user a human will take over]"
- Notify: [who/where, with what urgency]
```

---

### 5. `knowledge/[domain].md` -- Domain-Specific Reference

<!--
  These vary by use case. Examples:

  For customer service:
  - products.md (product catalog, pricing, specs)
  - policies.md (return policy, SLA, terms)
  - team.md (staff roster, schedules, skills)

  For data analysis:
  - schemas.md (database schemas, table descriptions)
  - metrics.md (KPI definitions, calculation methods)
  - sources.md (data sources, access methods, refresh schedules)

  For operations:
  - runbooks.md (step-by-step procedures for incidents)
  - contacts.md (on-call roster, vendor contacts)
  - systems.md (infrastructure inventory, dependencies)
-->

**General format:**

```markdown
# [DOMAIN] Reference

## [CATEGORY]

| Field1 | Field2 | Field3 | Notes |
|--------|--------|--------|-------|
| ...    | ...    | ...    | ...   |
```

**Rules:**
- Use tables over prose (faster for the agent to parse)
- Include a "last updated" date at the top
- Keep entries factual -- no opinions or analysis

---

## Knowledge Maintenance

### Agent Updates
The agent can and should update knowledge files when it discovers:
- New questions that should be in the FAQ
- New patterns or anti-patterns
- Corrections to existing entries

### Human Review
- Review agent-added entries weekly
- Prune outdated information monthly
- Validate accuracy of any auto-generated content

### Versioning
- Keep knowledge files in version control
- Major changes should be noted in commit messages
- If an entry is removed, note why (was it wrong, or just outdated?)
